t and current Conrad scholarship while drawing from Aristotle’s Poetics, Politics, and Nicomachean Ethics to offer original philosophical analyses of Conrad’s works. Drawing on Aristotle, Hannis provides a fresh context for making sense of Conrad’s self-differentiation from modernity. As a result, The Discerning Narrator provides an affirmation of literature’s invitation to wonder about the possibilities inherent in human nature, including the potential for painful depravity, heroic excellence, and ordinary human happiness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAristotle.  aBritish literature.  aConrad and ethics.  aConrad and philosophy.  aJoseph Conrad.  aLord Jim.  aNicomachean Ethics.  aagency.  ahistory of ideas.  aliterature and ethics.  amodern fiction.  amodernity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107973670 cprintz978144264907140uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144261936440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442619364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442619364/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK